  "human": {
    "description": "Conveys technical and scientific information with clarity, accuracy, and appropriate context for the audience. In a regulated pharmaceutical environment, precise communication reduces ambiguity, supports auditability, and accelerates decision-making across cross-functional teams.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You communicate the substance of your own work clearly in familiar contexts, such as stand-ups, pull request descriptions, and tickets. You ask clarifying questions when requirements are ambiguous and document decisions you make on tasks you own. You are learning to distinguish facts from assumptions and to cite sources such as SOPs, validated specifications, or regulatory references when relevant.",
      "developing": "You tailor written and verbal communication to your immediate audience, separating observations, interpretations, and recommendations. You produce design notes, incident summaries, and review comments that others can act on without needing to re-ask. You consistently flag uncertainty, link to supporting evidence, and adjust technical depth depending on whether you are speaking with engineers, QA, or validation partners.",
      "practicing": "You communicate complex technical topics concisely across multiple stakeholder groups, including scientists, regulatory reviewers, and senior engineers. Your specifications, RFCs, and post-incident reports are precise enough to serve as durable artifacts and stand up to audit. You proactively surface risks, trade-offs, and open questions, and you align teams around shared terminology rather than letting parallel vocabularies persist.",
      "role_modeling": "You set the standard for clarity within your area, coaching others to write and speak with precision and to ground statements in evidence. You facilitate difficult cross-functional discussions, translating between domains such as software engineering, computational biology, and GxP compliance without losing fidelity. Your communication artifacts are routinely reused as templates, and you intervene constructively when ambiguity threatens delivery, quality, or patient safety.",
      "exemplifying": "You shape how the organization communicates about engineering, influencing standards for documentation, decision records, and regulatory-facing technical writing. You can distil highly complex, multi-system problems into accurate narratives that align executives, regulators, and engineering leaders on a common course of action. Your precision is a force multiplier: it shortens debates, prevents costly misinterpretation, and strengthens trust with auditors, partners, and health authorities."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Unambiguous, Evidence-Linked Output",
    "workingStyle": "The agent communicates in clear, structured language, explicitly separating facts, assumptions, and recommendations and citing the specific code, data, SOPs, or specifications it relied on. It states uncertainty and open questions directly rather than implying confidence, and it adapts terminology and depth to the requesting role while preserving regulatory and scientific accuracy."
  }
}

