{
  "name": "Think in Systems",
  "human": {
    "description": "Systems thinking is the discipline of understanding how components, processes, and people interact within a larger whole rather than treating issues in isolation. In a regulated pharmaceutical context, it means tracing the connections between data, equipment, processes, quality, and patient outcomes so that changes are made with full awareness of their downstream effects.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You recognise that your work sits within a wider system and ask questions to understand how your component connects to upstream and downstream processes. You begin to notice when a local fix may have broader implications and seek guidance before acting. Your view is still largely focused on your immediate task, but you are actively building awareness of adjacent systems, validation boundaries, and quality controls.",
      "developing": "You routinely consider how your changes affect connected systems, data flows, and validated processes before committing to a solution. You map dependencies, trace inputs and outputs, and anticipate common second-order effects on quality, compliance, and operations. You consult colleagues to validate your understanding and adjust your approach when feedback reveals gaps in the bigger picture.",
      "practicing": "You consistently analyse problems across technical, process, and organisational boundaries, identifying feedback loops, bottlenecks, and risk concentrations. You weigh trade-offs between local optimisation and system health, and you communicate these trade-offs clearly to peers and stakeholders. Your designs reliably account for regulatory, manufacturing, and patient-impact considerations rather than just functional correctness.",
      "role_modeling": "You shape how your team frames problems, guiding others to look beyond symptoms to underlying system dynamics and unintended consequences. You facilitate cross-functional conversations that surface hidden dependencies between engineering, quality, manufacturing, and clinical domains. Your mentoring and reviews visibly raise the systemic awareness of those around you, and your decisions consistently prevent downstream issues that less experienced engineers would miss.",
      "exemplifying": "You set the standard for systems thinking across the organisation, influencing strategy, architecture, and ways of working so that systemic perspectives are embedded by default. You identify structural patterns that span products, platforms, and regulatory frameworks, and you drive change that improves whole-system outcomes for patients, regulators, and the business. Leaders and peers seek your perspective on the most ambiguous, high-stakes problems where the interactions matter more than any single component."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Whole-System Reasoning",
    "workingStyle": "The agent explicitly maps dependencies, data flows, and regulatory and quality impacts before proposing changes, and surfaces downstream and upstream consequences alongside its recommendations. It frames trade-offs in terms of overall system health rather than local optimisation, and flags assumptions about boundaries, interfaces, and validated states for human review."
  }
}

